{
  "texts": [
    "Otto Warburg and colleagues first discovered that tumor cells tend to convert oxidative metabolism into fermentation metabolism (55).",
    "In normal cells, most of the pyruvate formed by glycolysis enters the tricarboxylic acid cycle and is oxidized through oxidative phosphorylation (OXPHOS) (56).",
    "In contrast, in tumor cells, most pyruvate is converted into lactate through fermentation, a phenomenon known as the \"Warburg effect\" (57, 58).",
    "Through competitive uptake of glucose, cancer cells gain a survival advantage over normal cells through metabolic adaptations in oxygen-limited conditions.",
    "Moreover, cancer cells need to use their nutrient inputs as cellular building blocks."
  ]
}